<p class="p">The methods we investigated generally had similar effects on 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M81" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> across cities; in other words, increasing the thresholds in the increments we considered from 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M82" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> to 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M83" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">4</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and from 0% to 100% and reducing the slope by 0–25% were all associated with broadly linear declines in 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M84" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> as the magnitude of assumed adaptation increased (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f2" class="xref">Figure 2</xref>). The analog ERF method, however, resulted in more disparate estimates of 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M85" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. There were large differences between adaptation and no adaptation for some cities. For Ljubljana and London, 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M86" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> was 36 and 19 deaths per 100,000, respectively, with no adaptation and 2 and 6 deaths per 100,000, respectively, with adaptation (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f2" class="xref">Figure 2</xref>). This is equivalent to differences of 94% (Ljubljana) and 68% (London) between adaptation and no adaptation (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f3" class="xref">Figure 3</xref>). However, for other cities, the use of analog ERFs resulted in greater 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M87" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> with adaptation than without: for example, for Stockholm, Turin, and Valencia, where 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M88" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">Δ</mi>
    <mi class="mi">M</mi>
    <mi class="mi">o</mi>
    <mi class="mi">r</mi>
    <mi class="mi">t</mi>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
    <mi class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> was 16, 11, and 13 deaths per 100,000, respectively, without adaptation and 20, 20, and 92 deaths per 100,000, respectively, with adaptation (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f2" class="xref">Figure 2</xref>).
</p>
